Environment-climate : for a European New Deal
BRUSSELS – In Brussels as in European capitals, the "Green New Deal" is on everyone's lips, echoing the visionary economic program launched by President Franklin D. Roosevelt in 1933.
This time, however, it is about the environment and climate.
And Europe is the continent where we can and must act.
The European Union's engagement on these issues is not new: we have had a common program since 1972.
Later in 2005, the EU established the first emissions trading system, which remains the world's largest CO2 market.
And in 2015, the EU played a leading role in negotiating the Paris Agreement, committing to reduce its own greenhouse gas emissions by 40% (based on 1990 levels).
But these measures, important as they are, are not sufficient to address the challenges facing today's world.
Rising temperatures could lead to the complete disappearance of the Arctic ice cap by 2050.
The bees and many other insects are dying out, while microplastic pollution is ubiquitous in our environment.
And those suffering from respiratory diseases are becoming more numerous as air pollution gets worse.
We still have reasons to remain optimistic.
Look at these people, growing in number day by day, ready to act to challenge their lifestyles. Like these students and entire families descending into the streets of Stockholm, Prague, Brussels, and Milan every Thursday!
Businesses are also getting involved, seeing the unparalleled economic potential of a green economy.
But it is the politicians and policymakers, at both the national and European levels, who too often lack ambition.
We have a window of opportunity to act. Let's seize it!
And let us make a green Europe our top political priority for the years ahead, focused on three key fronts.
Firstly, Europe must become a carbon-neutral economy by 2050.
If we want to limit global warming to 1.5°C, we have no other choice: net CO2 emissions from the EU must be brought to zero by mid-century.
Together, we can massively invest in the future of our mobility, energy-efficient buildings and renewable energies, as well as key technologies such as hydrogen batteries, next-generation solar panels, and green chemistry.
Together, we must also apply strict CO2 emission limits to new private cars, public transport, as well as commercial maritime and air transportation.
And, by working closely with our automotive industry, we can make Europe the first continent of electric vehicles by 2030.
Secondly, Europe must play a leading role in responsible resource use and become a true circular economy that is waste-saving.
Every year, 8 billion tonnes of materials are transformed into energy or products in the European Union.
But only 0.6 billion tonnes come from recycling.
We must do much better, which will require focusing on four aspects: food waste and bioeconomy, textiles, construction, and rapidly evolving consumer goods.
Let us get to work today by launching, for example, a European initiative to combat planned obsolescence of household appliances and electronics, and by eliminating plastics from our value chains.
Thirdly, we must do much more to protect biodiversity.
The World Wildlife Fund reports that populations of wild species have declined by about 60% worldwide since 1970.
The United Nations conference on biodiversity, which will take place in Beijing next year, will be decisive.
Once again, the EU must set the example.
We must strengthen the EU legislation on species protection and put forward an ambitious plan for the blue economy and the conservation of our seas.
We also need to launch a genuine debate with our farmers (not against them!) on revising our standards and modernizing the common agricultural policy to support this green transition.
But these colossal tasks that lie ahead of us, we will not be able to accomplish them if it is always the same – and the most vulnerable – who are asked to bear their costs.
All the measures envisaged must therefore be designed first and foremost to minimize social costs.
And at the same time, we must work with our partners today for international cooperation, fighting against unfair competition.
Because it is useless to have strict European rules on pesticides or forest management if our imported food and wood are produced without respecting sustainability criteria.
These three areas could become the pillars of a Sustainability Pact at the heart of the new EU political cycle.
Since we are in an acute ecological debt, it would be fully justified that the stability and growth pact applicable to the public finances of member states finds an equivalent for green objectives!
To achieve its goals, this Sustainability Pact will require coordinated action in all fields: climate, trade, taxation, agriculture, and innovation.
The EU should not fear to use its regulatory powers, for example: expanding the scope of eco-design legislation and the "extended producer responsibility" could significantly stimulate environmental innovation.
Massive investments will also be necessary.
The European Commission estimates that the EU will need an additional 180 billion euros in investment each year to meet its commitments within the Paris Agreement framework.
This is a feasible goal.
The European Investment Bank is already the largest multilateral provider of climate-focused funds.
And the new EU budget and investment plan, taking full advantage of private sector investments, could still strengthen the Union's leverage.
The financial sector must play a fundamental role: through climate-related financial disclosure, we can encourage the world's largest financial institutions, such as Norway’s sovereign wealth fund and BlackRock, to adopt a longer-term perspective and avoid what Bank of England Governor Mark Carney termed the "horizon problem."
Finally, while some member states may see this as a risky project, we must have a debate on taxation, but also on subsidies for fossil fuels. In short, on integrating sustainability into public spending.
Behind these initiatives, the key lies in the approach. For the "Green New Deal" to succeed, we need to set ambitious goals and short- and long-term 'missions' that resonate socially.
With member states and the European Parliament, we must determine a common roadmap and conduct in-depth discussions, just as with our regions, cities, businesses, trade unions, and civil society.
Tout cela ne peut pas être fait du jour au lendemain.
Mais nous ne pouvons plus fermer les yeux et retenir notre respiration pour échapper à la réalité de notre environnement.
Il est déjà très tard pour lancer un « Green New Deal » européen. Mais il n’est pas trop tard.
Ne ratons pas cette nouvelle opportunité !
